  }
  Control <|-- DeletionActuationControl : is
  DeletionActuationControl "1" o--> "1" StateObjectArchetype : definesDeletedStateOf

  class AcquisitionActuationControl {
    +getStateObjectArchetype(): StateObjectArchetype
    +getStateObjectSelector(): String
  }
  Control <|-- AcquisitionActuationControl : is
  AcquisitionActuationControl "1" o--> "1" StateObjectArchetype : definesAcquiredStateOf

  ' ============================================================
  ' SOURCE MAPPING
  ' ============================================================

  class SourceMapping {
    +getValueMapping(): String
  }

  note top of SourceMapping
    Captures, at design time, how an effector's produced event instance is
    constructed from one or more source events and scalars.

    This enables end-to-end data transformation traceability.

    The mapping is represented as a declarative value mapping specification.
    It is intentionally *not* decomposed as one object per target property to
    keep the conceptual model compact while still supporting property-level
    lineage.

    Example structure (illustrative):
    - keys: target property paths
    - values: source event property paths OR JSON literals

    A SourceEventPropertyPath includes the reference to the source event
    archetype it is defined on.

    **Event Mapping Rules**
    - For each effector event source mapping M:
      - Ensure M.targetEventArchetype == effector.on (target event archetype).
    - Ensure a receptor exists for each distinct source event archetype
      referenced by any SourceEventPropertyPath in M.valueMapping.
    - Ensure a rule exists for each such distinct source event archetype,
      with triggering event == that source event archetype.
    - Ensure a rule effect exists in that rule which selects the effector.
    - When multiple rule effects exist in a rule, order deterministically
      (e.g. by effector name) to keep regeneration idempotent.

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - A mapping MUST reference exactly one target event archetype (the one
      bound to the effector).
    - A mapping MAY reference zero or more source event archetypes via
      SourceEventPropertyPath values (and may be literals-only).
    - Each valueMapping key MUST be a TargetEventPropertyPath valid with respect
      to M.targetEventArchetype's schema.
    - Each valueMapping value MUST be either:
      - a SourceEventPropertyPath valid with respect to the schema of its
        referenced source event archetype, OR
      - a JsonLiteral value.
    - For each (targetPath -> value) entry, the value type MUST be compatible
      with the type of the target property specified by the target event
      archetype schema at targetPath:
      - If value is a SourceEventPropertyPath, the referenced source property
        type MUST match (or be safely coercible to) the target property type.
      - If value is a JsonLiteral, the JSON value MUST validate against the
        target property type.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- SourceMapping : is

  ' ============================================================
  ' ACTUATION
  ' ============================================================

  class Actuation {
    +getName(): String
    +getType(): ActuationType
    +getStateObjectArchetype(): StateObjectArchetype
  }

  note top of Actuation
    An actuation declares an operational intent to change a state object,
    expressed as a behavioral rule control.

    **Systemic Semantics**:
    - Actuation is declared by a Control.
    - An Actuator is composed from this Actuation to execute the
      control's effect on the target state object.

    **Auto Definition Rules**:
    - When an Actuation is declared, the system MUST auto-define:
      - An Actuator composed by the Actuation.
      - A receptor on the actuator bound to the control effector's event
        archetype.
      - An effector on the actuator bound to an auto-defined ActuationEvent
        archetype.

    **Validation Rules**:
    - The control effector's event archetype MUST be a subtype of
      ActuationControlEventSchema.
    - The auto-defined actuation event archetype MUST be a subtype of
      ActuationEventSchema.
    - The target state object archetype MUST belong to the same System as the
      actuator mechanism, or to a subsystem that explicitly shares that
      state object resource with the actuator's system.

    **Incoherences / Drifts**:
    - Actuation declared without an actuator or without required receptor/
      effector bindings.
    - Actuation control event archetype not conforming to
      ActuationControlEventSchema.
    - Actuation event archetype not conforming to ActuationEventSchema.
    - Target state object archetype outside the actuator system boundary and
      not shared via subsystem governance.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Actuation : is
  Actuation "1" o--> "1" StateObjectArchetype : actuates

  enum ActuationType {
    CREATION
    MODIFICATION
    DELETION
    ACQUISITION
  }

  ' ============================================================
  ' SENSING
  ' ============================================================

  class Sensing {
    +getName(): String
    +getActuation(): Actuation
    +getSensor(): Sensor
    +getActuationEventArchetype(): EventArchetype
    +getFeedbackEventArchetype(): EventArchetype
    +getControlFeedbackReceptor(): Receptor
  }

  note top of Sensing
    A sensing links actuation execution to feedback reception, enabling
    homeostatic loops on actuations.

    **Systemic Semantics**:
    - Sensing observes the event emitted by the actuator and forwards feedback
      to a control feedback receptor.

    **Auto Definition Rules**:
    - A Sensing (and its Sensor) MUST be auto-defined only if the
      declaring Control defines a feedback receptor.
    - The sensor MUST have a receptor bound to the actuator effector's
      actuation event archetype.
    - The sensor MUST have an effector bound to the feedback receptor's event
      archetype.

    **Validation Rules**:
    - The feedback event archetype MUST be a subtype of
      ActuationFeedbackEventSchema.

    **Incoherences / Drifts**:
    - Sensing defined without a control feedback receptor.
    - Sensor mechanism missing receptor/effector bindings to actuation/feedback
      event archetypes.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Sensing : is
  Sensing "1" o--> "1" Actuation : observes
  Sensing "1" *--> "1" Sensor : composes
  Sensing "1" o--> "1" EventArchetype : actuationEvent
  Sensing "1" o--> "1" EventArchetype : feedbackEvent
  Sensing "1" o--> "0..1" Receptor : controlFeedbackReceptor

  ' ============================================================
  ' COMPONENT
  ' ============================================================

  class Component {
    +getName(): String
    +getFunctions(): Function[]
    +getModalities(): Modality[]
    +getMechanisms(): Mechanism[]
    +getInteractions(): Interaction[]
    +getInterfaces(): Interface[]
  }

  note top of Component
    A component is a structural grouping primitive used to present and manage
    internal architecture.

    Components do not necessarily expose interfaces to the outside of the
    system.

    **Systemic Semantics**:
    - A component groups structural and behavioral primitives to provide a
      manageable internal architecture view of a system.
    - A component is not required to align with an external boundary; it may be
      entirely internal.

    **Attribute Semantics**:
    - "name": Human-readable semantic identifier.
    - "functions": Functions allocated to / realized by the component.
    - "modalities": Modalities supported/managed by mechanisms in the
      component.
    - "mechanisms": Mechanisms belonging to the component.
    - "interfaces": Interfaces regrouped by the component (may be internal or
      external).
    - "interactions": Interactions in which the component participates.

    **Derivation Rules**:
    - "interfaces" MAY be computed from mechanisms grouped by the component.
    - "interactions" MAY be computed from:
      - interactions carried by channels of those interfaces, and/or
      - interactions whose effector/receptor is owned by those mechanisms.

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - "name" MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all components of the same system.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Component : is
  Component "1" o--> "1..*" Function : regroups
  Component "1" o--> "0..*" Modality : regroups
  Component "1" o--> "1..*" Mechanism : regroups
  Component "1" o--> "0..*" Interaction : regroups
  Component "1" o--> "0..*" Interface : regroups

  ' ============================================================
  ' INTERFACE
  ' ============================================================

  class Interface {
    +getName(): String
    +getReceptors(): Receptor[]
    +getEffectors(): Effector[]
    +getChannels(): Channel[]
  }

  note top of Interface
    An interface is an interaction surface of a system or component.

    Interfaces can be purely internal (structuring internal architecture) or
    external (participating in a system boundary).

    **Systemic Semantics**:
    - Interfaces group receptors and effectors to make interaction points
      explicit.
    - Channels are structural carriers that connect interfaces.

    **Attribute Semantics**:
    - "name": Human-readable semantic identifier.
    - "receptors": Receptors regrouped by the interface.
    - "effectors": Effectors regrouped by the interface.
    - "channels": Channels for which this interface is an endpoint.

    **Derivation Rules** (non-normative):
    - "receptors" and "effectors" MAY be computed from the interactions carried
      by the interface's channels (collecting interaction.receptor and
      interaction.effector, respectively).
    - "channels" MAY be computed from boundary/external connectivity design.
    - "channels" MAY also be computed as all channels for which this interface
      is an endpoint.

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - "name" MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all interfaces of the same system.
    - An interface MUST regroup at least one receptor.
    - An interface MUST regroup at least one effector.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Interface : is
  Interface "1" o--> "1..*" Receptor : regroups
  Interface "1" o--> "1..*" Effector : regroups
  Interface "1" *--> "0..*" Channel : has

  ' ============================================================
  ' CHANNEL
  ' ============================================================

  class Channel {
    +getName(): String
    +getProtocol(): String
    +getInteractions(): Interaction[]
    +getInterfaceA(): Interface
    +getInterfaceB(): Interface
  }

  note top of Channel
    A channel is a structural carrier that mediates interactions.

    A channel connects exactly two interfaces (interface A and interface B).

    Endpoints are intentionally unordered at this abstraction level; any
    directionality (client/server, producer/consumer, origin/destination) is a
    property of specific interactions carried by the channel.

    **Systemic Semantics**:
    - Channels model *how* exchanges are carried (transport/medium), not their
      meaning.
    - Multiple interactions may be carried by the same channel.

    **Attribute Semantics**:
    - "name": Human-readable semantic identifier.
    - "protocol": The exchange protocol/medium (e.g., HTTP, Kafka, in-memory).
    - "interactions": Interactions carried by the channel.
    - "interface A": One endpoint interface of the channel.
    - "interface B": The other endpoint interface of the channel.

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - "name" MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all channels of the same system.
    - "interface A" MUST be defined.
    - "interface B" MUST be defined.
    - "interface A" MUST NOT be the same as "interface B".
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Channel : is
  Channel "1" o--> "0..*" Interaction : carries
  Channel "1" o--> "1" Interface : interfaceA
  Channel "1" o--> "1" Interface : interfaceB

  ' ============================================================
  ' INTERACTION
  ' ============================================================

  class Interaction {
    +getName(): String
    +getEffector(): Effector
    +getReceptor(): Receptor
  }

  note top of Interaction
    An interaction is an event exchange relationship between mechanisms.

    Interactions may be internal to a system (no channel, no external
    interface) or external (carried by channels bound to interfaces).

    **Systemic Semantics**:
    - An interaction is an atomic causal coupling from a producing effector to
      a receiving receptor.
    - The interaction's meaning is about *what* is exchanged, not the transport
      mechanism; transport may be modeled via channels.

    **Attribute Semantics**:
    - "name": Human-readable semantic identifier.
    - "effector": The producing endpoint emitting an event instance.
    - "receptor": The receiving endpoint consuming an event instance.

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - "name" MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all interactions of the same system.
    - "effector" MUST be defined.
    - "receptor" MUST be defined.
    - The event archetype produced by "effector" MUST be compatible with the
      event archetype received by "receptor".
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Interaction : is
  Interaction "1" o--> "1" Effector : has
  Interaction "1" o--> "1" Receptor :  has

  ' ============================================================
  ' MECHANISM
  ' ============================================================

  abstract class Mechanism {
    +getName(): String
    +getReceptors(): Receptor[]
    +getEffectors(): Effector[]
  }

  note top of Mechanism
    A mechanism represents a system's capability to process input events
    received via its receptors, and produce output events via its effectors.

    A mechanism represents an atomic causal unit of behavior within a system.

    **PPRC ↔ Behavior Anchor:**
    The Mechanism is the **correlation point** between governance definitions
    (PPRC) and observable behavior:
    - **Definition side**: a Mechanism is bound by the Receptors and
      Effectors of the Rules/Controls it implements. Its structure is
      deterministically derived from PPRC (see Rule: Mechanism
      Auto-Definition Rule).
    - **Observation side**: DSM observes Mechanism behavior (events
      received/emitted, sequences, timing). Conformance appraisal compares
      observed Mechanism behavior against the Rules/Controls that defined it.
    - The Mechanism is therefore the unit of both **Realization** (executing
      definitions) and **Observation** (what DSM watches).

    **Positional semantics (GRS&CO):**
    The mechanism subtypes (Governor, Regulator, Supervisor, Coordinator,
    Operator, Actuator, Sensor) are **positional labels**, not absolute roles.
    A mechanism's label is determined by its function relative to the system
    scope it governs. A Governor in one system may be an Operator from a
    supersystem's perspective (heterarchy; second-order observer dependence
    — von Foerster). This is consistent with OrganizationalRelationship.

    **Layer and plane placement:**
    - Governor belongs to the **Governance plane** (Reflexive Layer).
    - Regulator belongs to the **Regulation plane** (Reflexive Layer).
    - Supervisor belongs to the **Supervision plane** (Reflexive Layer).
    - Coordinator belongs to the **Coordination plane** (Reflexive Layer).
    - Operator belongs to the **Operation plane** (Ontic Layer).
    - Actuator belongs to the **Operation plane** (Ontic Layer).
    - Sensor belongs to the **Operation plane** (Ontic Layer).

    **Definition instance vs. operational instance:**
    GSM readers must distinguish two instance levels for every Mechanism:
    - **Definition instance**: a GSM primitive stored in the Definition
      Manager. It describes the mechanism's receptors, effectors, the
      Rules/Controls it implements, and its governance authority. This is
      a model artifact — it does not execute anything by itself.
    - **Operational instance**: a runtime process in a SIE plane (for
      Reflexive mechanisms) or in the tenant's state plane (for some
      Ontic mechanisms). The operational instance is instantiated FROM
      the definition instance and executes its behavior.

    The same definition instance may have zero or more operational
    instances (e.g., no instance if the Rule is DRAFT; multiple
    instances if deployed across environments). The definition instance
    is the governance anchor; the operational instance is the execution
    artifact.

    Example: "the Governor mechanism of system S" is a definition
    instance in the Definition Manager. It does NOT run inside system S.
    Its operational instance runs inside SIE's Governance plane.

    **Operational ownership (SIE architecture):**
    Reflexive Layer mechanisms (Governor, Regulator, Supervisor, Coordinator)
    are operationally realized by SIE's corresponding planes. Their
    definitions are GSM primitives; their runtime instances are SIE
    processes. SIE's purpose is to automate the Reflexive Layer of any
    system it governs.

    Ontic Layer mechanisms (Operator, Actuator, Sensor) have two possible
    definition semantics:
    - **SIE Operator definition**: defines a mechanism that SIE's
      Operation plane instantiates and executes. The SIE Operator
      operates the state plane by applying definitions of other
      PPRC primitives (executing Rules, sequencing Controls,
      commanding Actuators). Agency: SIE acts.
    - **Domain Operator definition**: defines a pre-existing domain
      mechanism (software function, infrastructure component, human
      procedure) in the tenant's state plane. The domain Operator
      already exists and acts; SIE Supervises its behavior and may
      command it through SIE Operators and Actuators. Agency: tenant
      acts, SIE oversees.
    - **Actuators and Sensors** follow the same dual definition
      semantics: either SIE-owned (SIE connector/adapter) or
      domain-owned (tenant-side component that SIE commands or
      receives events from). See Actuator and Sensor notes.

    Both definition semantics share the same GSM structure (receptors,
    effectors, PPRC chain, governance authority). The distinction appears
    at realization time: who instantiates and runs the operational
    instance.

    **Generative semantics (GSM is prescriptive, not descriptive):**
    In both cases, the GSM definition is a **to-be prescription** — it
    defines what the mechanism MUST be and do. Whether a domain
    mechanism already exists in the state plane is a DSM observation
    (as-is), not a GSM concern.
    - In **normal mode**: the user or Determination process defines
      Domain Operator/Actuator/Sensor definitions as governance
      targets. Conformance Appraisal then measures the gap between
      the definition (to-be) and the DSM observation (as-is).
    - In **discovery mode**: DSM observes domain mechanisms that have
      no corresponding GSM definition. Emergence (Determination
      sub-type) proposes new GSM definitions from those observations.
    The definition itself remains prescriptive in both modes.

    **Sensor vs. Supervisor / Actuator vs. Operator (scope distinction):**
    Sensors and Actuators are NOT redundant with the Supervision and
    Operation planes. The distinction is abstraction level:
    - **Sensor**: microscopic observation — observes a specific
      Actuation's effect and produces a feedback event. Scope:
      one Actuation feedback loop. Analogy: the thermometer.
    - **Supervisor**: macroscopic evaluation — evaluates policy/rule
      compliance using inputs from many sources (Sensor feedback,
      monitoring telemetry, CMDB data, etc.). Scope: the full
      governance PPRC chain. Analogy: the thermostat logic.
    - **Actuator**: microscopic execution — performs a specific CRUD
      operation on a state object. Scope: one Actuation. Analogy:
      the relay switching the heater.
    - **Operator**: macroscopic execution — implements complete Rules,
      sequences Controls, commands Actuators. Scope: the full
      behavioral rule chain. Analogy: the HVAC controller.

    Closed-loop flow using all four:
      State → **Sensor** (observe actuation) → **Supervisor** (evaluate
      compliance) → Regulator (adjust definitions) → **Operator**
      (implement rule) → **Actuator** (change state) → State

    **SIE availability invariant (architectural):**
    SIE automates the Reflexive Layer but does NOT replace governance
    itself. SIE is designed to be pluggable and synchronized with
    tenant tools (Jira, Confluence, CMDB, monitoring platforms, etc.),
    delivering governance definitions and specifications to those
    systems. SIE's integrations are Capacities of the SIE system;
    tenants are responsible for connecting their tools to SIE.

    If SIE becomes unavailable, governance artifacts already delivered
    to tenant tools remain accessible and actionable by human
    governance. SIE makes governance infinitely better — it does not
    make governance impossible without it.

    This is an architectural invariant, not a discovered property:
    SIE availability enhances tenant governance capability, but is not
    a precondition for tenant governance existence.

    **Governance authority (not composition):**
    GRS&CO mechanisms have governance authority over PPRC artifacts
    (Governor governs Principles, Regulator governs Policies/Rules/Controls,
    Supervisor enforces them). But PPRC artifacts are NOT structurally
    composed by Mechanisms — the relationship is governance authority
    (association, o-->), not UML composition (*-->). The generative direction
    is the reverse: PPRC definitions → auto-define Mechanism definitions
    (via Rule: Mechanism Auto-Definition Rule).

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - "name" MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all mechanisms of the same system.
    - A mechanism MUST have at least one receptor and one effector.
    - If a mechanism is deleted, its receptors and effectors MUST be
      deleted.
    - If a receptor or effector is deleted, the mechanism MUST NOT be deleted,
      except if the receptor or effector is the last one the mechanism owns.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Mechanism : is
  Mechanism "1" *--> "1..*" Receptor : has
  Mechanism "1" *--> "1..*" Effector : has

  ' ============================================================
  ' ACTUATOR
  ' ============================================================

  class Actuator {
    +getActuation(): Actuation
  }

  note top of Actuator
    An actuator is a microscopic execution mechanism that performs a
    specific state object mutation (CRUD) as declared by an Actuation.

    Actuators are auto-defined from an Actuation declared by a
    behavioral rule control. They are NOT redundant with Operators:
    an Operator implements a complete Rule and sequences Controls;
    an Actuator executes one specific Actuation within that sequence.
    Analogy: Operator = HVAC controller; Actuator = relay switching
    the heater.

    **Attribute Semantics**:
    - "actuation": The actuation declaration from which the actuator is
      derived.

    **Dual Definition Semantics (same pattern as Operator):**
    - **SIE Actuator**: SIE connector/adapter that calls tenant APIs
      or infrastructure to effect the state change.
    - **Domain Actuator**: prescriptive definition of what a
      tenant-side actuation component MUST do. SIE commands it
      through SIE Operators; conformance between this definition
      and the actual component is measured by Conformance Appraisal.

    **Auto Definition Rules**:
    - The actuator MUST operate on a state object archetype owned by
      the same System, or a subsystem that explicitly shares that state object
      resource with the actuator's System.
  end note

  Mechanism <|-- Actuator : is
  Actuator "1" o--> "1" Actuation : implements

  ' ============================================================
  ' SENSOR
  ' ============================================================

  class Sensor

  note top of Sensor
    A sensor is a microscopic observation mechanism that captures the
    effect of a specific Actuation and produces feedback events.

    Sensors are auto-defined from a Sensing linked to an Actuation,
    and only when a control feedback receptor exists. They are NOT
    redundant with Supervisors: a Supervisor macroscopically evaluates
    policy/rule compliance using many input sources; a Sensor
    microscopically observes one Actuation's outcome.
    Analogy: Sensor = thermometer; Supervisor = thermostat logic.

    **Dual Definition Semantics (same pattern as Operator):**
    - **SIE Sensor**: SIE polls/subscribes to tenant telemetry or
      state-plane events to observe actuation effects.
    - **Domain Sensor**: prescriptive definition of what a tenant
      monitoring component MUST produce (actuation feedback events).
      Conformance between this definition and the actual component
      is measured by Conformance Appraisal.

    **Auto Definition Rules**:
    - For every event archetype E whose schema is a subtype of
      ActuationEventSchema, the sensor MUST have (or derive) a
      receptor bound to E.
    - For every receptor bound to E, the sensor MUST have an
      effector bound to event O whose schema is subtype of
      ActuationFeedbackEventSchema.
  end note

  Mechanism <|-- Sensor : is

  ' ============================================================
  ' RECEPTOR
  ' ============================================================

  class Receptor {
    +getName(): String
    +getReceivedEventArchetype(): EventArchetype
  }

  note top of Receptor
    A receptor represents a mechanism's capability to receive events produced by
    mechanism's effectors. Such received event represent a cause for the
    mechanism to operate.

    **Systemic Semantics**:
    Multiple receptors can listen to the same EventArchetype. This enables:
    - Multiple mechanisms to react to the same event type
    - Fan-out patterns where one event triggers many behaviors
    - Cross-component coordination via shared event contracts

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - "name" MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all receptors of the same system.
    - A receptor MUST be bound to exactly one event archetype.
    - An event archetype MAY be bound to multiple receptors (sharing allowed).
    - If the bound event archetype is deleted, all receptors bound to it MUST
      be deleted.
    - If a receptor is deleted, the bound event archetype MUST NOT be deleted
      (other receptors may still reference it).
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Receptor : is
  Receptor "0..*" o--> "1" EventArchetype : receives

  ' ============================================================
  ' EFFECTOR
  ' ============================================================

  class Effector {
    +getName(): String
    +getProducedEventArchetype(): EventArchetype
  }

  note top of Effector
    An effector represents a mechanism's capability to produce events. Such
    produced events represent the effect of a mechanism's operation on the
    system.

    **Systemic Semantics**:
    Multiple effectors can produce the same EventArchetype. This enables:
    - Multiple mechanisms to emit the same event type
    - Distributed event production (e.g., OrderCreatedEvent from different services)
    - Consistent event contracts across system components

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - "name" MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all effectors of the same system.
    - An effector MUST be bound to exactly one event archetype.
    - An event archetype MAY be bound to multiple effectors (sharing allowed).
    - If the bound event archetype is deleted, all effectors bound to it MUST
      be deleted.
    - If an effector is deleted, the bound event archetype MUST NOT be deleted
      (other effectors may still reference it).
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Effector : is
  Effector "0..*" o--> "1" EventArchetype : produces

  ' ============================================================
  ' EVENT ARCHETYPE
  ' ============================================================

  class EventArchetype {
    +getName(): String
    +getSchema(): ArchetypeSchema
  }

  note top of EventArchetype
    Defines the structure and semantics of an event that can be emitted or
    received by a system via its effectors and receptors.

    **Consistency Rules**
    - "name" MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all entities classified as "archetype".
    - "name" MUST match the name of the schema.
    - If its schema is deleted, the event archetype MUST be deleted.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- EventArchetype : is
  EventArchetype "0..*" o--> "1" ArchetypeSchema : has
  
  ' ============================================================
  ' STATE OBJECT ARCHETYPE
  ' ============================================================

  class StateObjectArchetype {
    +getName(): String
    +getSchema(): ArchetypeSchema
  }

  note top of StateObjectArchetype
    Defines the structure and semantics of a state object that can be used to
    represent the state of a system.

    StateObjectArchetype is a SystemicPrimitive. It models observable/mutable state,
    that models observable/mutable state, whereas SystemicPrimitives model
    structural/definitional constructs.

    **Rules**
    - "name" MUST match the name of the schema.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all entities classified as "archetype".
    - If its schema is deleted, the state object archetype MUST be deleted.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- StateObjectArchetype : is
  StateObjectArchetype "1" *--> "1" ArchetypeSchema : has

  ' ============================================================
  ' SYSTEMIC PROCESSES
  '
  ' GSM recognizes five canonical governance processes:
  '
  ' 1. Observation:  State → DSM (sense, describe)
  ' 2. Appraisal:    Evaluate (3 sub-types):
  '    - Conformance appraisal: DSM ↔ GSM (observed vs. defined)
  '    - Coherence appraisal: GSM ↔ GSM (intra-definitional consistency)
  '    - Coverage appraisal: completeness meta-check
  ' 3. Determination: Generative (3 sub-types):
  '    - Emergence: inductive (descriptions without definitions → proposals)
  '    - Adaptation: abductive (deviation evidence → rule adjustment)
  '    - Coherence restoration: corrective (contradiction → fix)
  ' 4. Realization:   GSM → State (actuate via Operator/Actuator mechanisms)
  ' 5. Stabilization: Cross-loop dampening (Coordination plane)
  '
  ' Emergent properties (NOT processes):
  ' - Homeostasis: operational loop stability
  ' - Autopoiesis: self-definition (system defines its own governance)
  ' - Viability: continued existence in environment
  ' ============================================================

}

@enduml
